  "prompt": "Where can Typhoons happen and how are they formed?",
  "response": "Typhoons can occur in the Northwest Pacific Basin, which includes areas near the Philippines, Japan, China, and other parts of East and Southeast Asia. Here's how they form:\n\nFormation Process:\n1. Warm ocean water (at least 80\u00b0F/26.5\u00b0C)\n2. Moist air rising from the ocean's surface\n3. Low wind shear (minimal change in wind speed/direction with height)\n4. Warm core low-pressure system develops\n5. Winds start rotating around a calm center (eye)\n6. As wind speeds increase, the system becomes a typhoon\n\nSpecific Conditions for Formation:\n- Usually form between June and November\n- Typically develop over warm tropical oceans\n- Require ocean temperatures above 80\u00b0F\n- Need sufficient Coriolis effect to create rotation\n- Need atmospheric conditions that support vertical development\n\nSimilar storms in other regions:\n- Hurricanes (Atlantic Ocean and Eastern Pacific)\n- Cyclones (Indian Ocean)\n\nThese powerful storms can have wind speeds exceeding 74 mph (119 km/h) and cause significant damage through:\n- Strong winds\n- Heavy rainfall\n- Storm surges\n- Coastal flooding\n\nUnderstanding their formation helps in prediction and preparation.",
